WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.560
Hi, welcome to my talk.

00:00:08.560 --> 00:00:09.560
My name is Albert Rapp.

00:00:09.560 --> 00:00:12.320
I am a freelancer and a content creator.

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:16.440
You may have seen some of my content on YouTube or Twitter.

00:00:16.440 --> 00:00:22.280
On my main job, I am a math PhD student focusing on probability theory, but I assure you that

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:25.120
today we are definitely not talking about mathematics.

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:31.799
Today I want to show you how to combine HTML and CSS with popular R tools that you may

00:00:31.799 --> 00:00:36.759
already use to create even more beautiful outputs than we already have with the tools

00:00:36.759 --> 00:00:37.820
we want.

00:00:37.820 --> 00:00:43.799
So you may be wondering why is a mathematician talking about things like making more beautiful

00:00:43.799 --> 00:00:50.279
designs, making better tables with GT, having a nicer plot, talking about things like design.

00:00:50.279 --> 00:00:55.520
So let me tell you how I ended up here and how the idea for this talk came to be.

00:00:55.520 --> 00:01:00.799
As a PhD student, I also have to teach, and at some point, at that time, I felt like I

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:04.639
was getting stuck with the R course and not with the math course.

00:01:04.639 --> 00:01:09.800
So I was sort of getting stuck with having to teach R. I assure you now I would be very

00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:14.199
glad about this, but at that time, I felt like I was kind of getting the short end

00:01:14.199 --> 00:01:16.160
of the stick.

00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:21.440
But I decided to make the best out of it, so I decided to read R for data science, which

00:01:21.440 --> 00:01:25.800
I am sure all of you have read, and I just learned a lot from it.

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:31.959
And one of the things that I found very striking was that it starts out with data visualization.

00:01:31.959 --> 00:01:37.919
The very first chapter teaches you ggplot, and to me, it was fascinating how just the

00:01:37.919 --> 00:01:44.959
very basic ggplot call that you learn in the first page of that chapter was already creating

00:01:44.959 --> 00:01:50.519
a plot that was much nicer than what I could have possibly created at that time.

00:01:50.519 --> 00:01:53.959
So we will see in this talk that this is a recurring theme.

00:01:53.959 --> 00:01:59.199
We have very great tools that can help you to create very nice outputs all from within

00:01:59.199 --> 00:02:01.320
a couple of lines.

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:04.879
So this is how I started ending up with data visualization.

00:02:04.879 --> 00:02:10.279
I wanted to learn more, and I kind of went down a rabbit hole, learned more about it,

00:02:10.279 --> 00:02:14.720
and once you start learning about data viz, you see other people's work as well.

00:02:15.479 --> 00:02:20.199
And here I have brought data viz from John Burn Murdoch, who is creating visualizations

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:23.919
from the Financial Times, and if you don't know his work, you should definitely check

00:02:23.919 --> 00:02:24.919
it out.

00:02:24.919 --> 00:02:29.320
He creates beautiful plots, and what I found most interesting about this particular chart

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:34.720
is that instead of using a legend, like a typical legend on the right-hand side of the

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:42.000
plot to indicate which color means what, instead it highlights single words and colorizes them.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.360
For example, in the title you can see that the word British cities is colored in red

00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:51.320
and to indicate that the red dots mean British cities.

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:55.119
So I thought, well, can I do this in ggplot2?

00:02:55.119 --> 00:03:02.039
And so I set out and tried to create a scatterplot first using the very famous palmar penguins,

00:03:02.039 --> 00:03:05.479
and this is like a very nice plot that I created with ggplot.

00:03:05.479 --> 00:03:07.279
It's a decent plot.

00:03:07.399 --> 00:03:12.600
ggplot is a very fancy tool to make these kind of things, but this was not what I set

00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:13.720
out to do.

00:03:13.720 --> 00:03:18.279
I wanted to have the colors not on the right-hand side, but in the title.

00:03:18.279 --> 00:03:21.360
So the question is, can we do this within ggplot?

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:26.220
And the answer is, yeah, we can actually do that, but we have to invoke an extra package

00:03:26.220 --> 00:03:28.520
that's called ggtext.

00:03:28.520 --> 00:03:32.919
So at this point you are asking probably, okay, what's the story with HTML and CSS now,

00:03:32.919 --> 00:03:33.919
right?

00:03:33.919 --> 00:03:36.600
We have been saying all of this was done in R.

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:40.039
But if you are looking at what you have to do to make this happen, even though we are

00:03:40.039 --> 00:03:45.919
using R code, what you need to do is to wrap the words that you want to highlight into

00:03:45.919 --> 00:03:50.720
these span tags, and inside of these span tags you have to set the color to some hex

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:52.440
code that you want to use.

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:55.479
So really, this is HTML and CSS.

00:03:55.479 --> 00:04:02.199
These span tags, that's HTML, and the style instruction inside of it, that's CSS.

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:08.399
And even though we could get very far to accomplish our goal with just within R, we have a great

00:04:08.399 --> 00:04:09.399
tool for that.

00:04:09.399 --> 00:04:14.479
We had to sparkle in a little bit of HTML and CSS to make this happen.

00:04:14.479 --> 00:04:19.040
And the very nice thing is that it isn't actually that hard to make this work, right?

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:22.839
If you can create a scatterplot with ggplot like that, then you certainly won't have any

00:04:22.839 --> 00:04:29.640
trouble to set the words into span tags and then throw in a couple of keywords.

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:35.880
And we will see that this is a recurring theme with the tools that we like to use.

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:41.299
So I have mentioned that you can add a little bit of HTML and CSS to your data visualizations

00:04:41.299 --> 00:04:45.440
with ggplot, but it's also true for other very popular tools.

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:46.600
And this is what I've noticed.

00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:51.880
It's true for tables with GT, it's true for reports and slides with Quarto, and it's true

00:04:51.880 --> 00:04:54.359
for dashboards that you create with Shiny.

00:04:54.359 --> 00:04:58.679
All of these packages or tools are great out of the box.

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:04.440
They can create beautiful outputs, and we can get very far all from within that tool

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:05.760
that you use.

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:09.559
But if you want to make something unique, if you want to make something a little bit

00:05:09.559 --> 00:05:14.399
special like having the colors in the title instead, then you need to add a little bit

00:05:14.399 --> 00:05:17.279
of HTML and CSS to it.

00:05:17.279 --> 00:05:20.179
I like to compare this to building houses.

00:05:20.179 --> 00:05:26.000
You can create or can build a very nice, a very solid home all within R, nothing wrong

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:27.040
about that.

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:33.000
But if you want to build something very special, want to have something very fancy, then you

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.260
are kind of forced to add a little bit of HTML and CSS to it.

00:05:37.260 --> 00:05:41.480
But really the point that I want to make here is that just with the data visualization where

00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:46.040
you only had to throw in these span tags, it isn't that hard once you are at the point

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:48.600
that you can already create the nice home.

00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:53.679
So the transition using the HTML and CSS isn't that hard.

00:05:53.679 --> 00:05:56.600
To prove my point, let's look at a couple more examples.

00:05:56.600 --> 00:05:59.239
Here's a table that I have created with GT.

00:05:59.239 --> 00:06:03.000
Once again, it's a very amazing tool that we have at our disposal.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.480
GT can make a very nice table.

00:06:05.480 --> 00:06:06.920
Here it's a solid table.

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:12.279
It shows a couple of measurements from the penguins dataset, and it even has like a little

00:06:12.279 --> 00:06:16.839
chart in there to visualize the distribution of the penguin weights.

00:06:16.839 --> 00:06:21.239
And even though this is a neat table, it may be a bit boring.

00:06:21.239 --> 00:06:25.079
It's just plain black and white, and you may need to draw your reader's attention to

00:06:25.079 --> 00:06:28.040
that specific table that you have.

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:33.679
So you might want to throw in a little bit of color in there, add like a linear gradient

00:06:33.679 --> 00:06:37.880
to make things look fancy just to grab your reader's attention.

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:41.559
And the same story is here happening again.

00:06:41.559 --> 00:06:47.519
Basically, this was all done in GT, but to make this happen, you created your table in

00:06:47.519 --> 00:06:50.959
R and then passed this to some overlay.

00:06:50.959 --> 00:06:56.700
In this case, it's called OptCSS, where you stick in CSS code to make the final changes

00:06:56.700 --> 00:06:58.140
that you want.

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:03.160
And again, the story here is that the part that is highlighted is only a couple of keywords

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:07.119
that are pretty easy to understand.

00:07:07.119 --> 00:07:11.799
I will guess that you won't have any trouble understanding what border top width does when

00:07:11.799 --> 00:07:13.920
you set it to one pixel, right?

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:18.320
The only thing that might be a little bit troublesome is the things that are grayed

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:19.359
out here.

00:07:19.359 --> 00:07:23.480
These are the description of where you want to apply your styles.

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:27.899
But the cool thing about this is that usually you don't have to write these things yourself.

00:07:27.899 --> 00:07:31.279
You just have to figure out where to look, and then you copy and paste the thing and

00:07:31.279 --> 00:07:32.440
throw that in there.

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:34.000
So this is how I made this thing.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:38.640
I mean, I just copy and pasted the descriptions, and then I set the keywords to what I want.

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:40.279
And the keywords are easily Googled.

00:07:40.279 --> 00:07:44.320
If you want to figure out what changes the background in CSS, you Google just that, and

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:47.600
you see that background will do the job.

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:49.040
Same thing is true in Shiny.

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:53.640
In Shiny, you can just throw in a couple of keywords to a lot of UI elements to make your

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:56.399
user interface look different.

00:07:56.399 --> 00:08:02.239
And once you are comfortable with using these nice and easy keyword value pairs, you can

00:08:02.239 --> 00:08:09.760
start to use more complex stuff from CSS, like the grid alignment, to take your UI elements

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:14.200
that you have from within Shiny and arrange that on a grid here.

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:18.600
That's how I created the Shiny app, this little habit tracker.

00:08:18.600 --> 00:08:23.600
And basically, this is how I leveraged CSS here to get the job done.

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:30.239
And finally, we have Quarto, which I like to call a web development gateway drug.

00:08:30.239 --> 00:08:31.239
It really is true.

00:08:31.239 --> 00:08:36.760
Quarto generates so much great output for you out of the box, and a lot of times that's

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:38.520
HTML and CSS.

00:08:38.520 --> 00:08:43.960
And then you're thinking, OK, I want to change this tiny thing to make the theme similar

00:08:43.960 --> 00:08:45.159
to what I want.

00:08:45.159 --> 00:08:46.159
And then you're hooked.

00:08:46.159 --> 00:08:48.880
You want to figure out, how do I do this?

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:53.760
And this is really how you end up learning more about HTML and CSS, and this is how I

00:08:53.760 --> 00:08:55.799
ended up there, too.

00:08:55.799 --> 00:09:02.039
And the very cool thing is that Quarto is a great place to learn the HTML and CSS, because

00:09:02.039 --> 00:09:04.960
it already generates all of the code for you.

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:07.559
You just have to figure out where to look.

00:09:07.559 --> 00:09:11.640
Once you know that, you can copy and paste most of the code from there and change the

00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:12.919
values to what you want.

00:09:12.919 --> 00:09:17.599
If it says background is white, copy and paste it and set background to blue if that's what

00:09:17.599 --> 00:09:18.880
you need.

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:21.880
So with that, you can get very far.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:26.679
And the thing about Quarto is that, for example, if you create slides like these, you can do

00:09:26.679 --> 00:09:28.520
things like in little chunks.

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:34.479
For example, you could interpret every slide as a little web development project and do

00:09:34.479 --> 00:09:36.080
some fancy stuff there.

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:39.479
Here, I definitely want to mention that this theme isn't by me.

00:09:39.479 --> 00:09:41.640
It is great, but it is from Emil.

00:09:41.640 --> 00:09:42.640
I borrowed that.

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:48.640
He will speak about probably more amazing Quarto themes just after me.

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:53.000
And this saying of every slide is a little web development project is something I have

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:57.320
picked up from Garek Adembuyi, who also stressed this point.

00:09:57.320 --> 00:10:03.799
So it's not a new idea, but it is worth repeating that you can start working on very

00:10:04.119 --> 00:10:09.760
small projects to ease your way into the HTML and CSS world.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:12.640
So this begs the question, how do we actually start with that?

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:16.880
I gave you a couple of examples and showed you, like, after the fact, this is how it

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:17.880
was done.

00:10:17.880 --> 00:10:21.119
But how do we figure out these things?

00:10:21.119 --> 00:10:26.039
And again, Quarto is the base for us, our users, or Quarto users.

00:10:26.039 --> 00:10:31.400
It's the best way to start out because most of the things are already done for us.

00:10:31.400 --> 00:10:38.960
And in this case, you can use so-called SCSS variables to just throw in a SCSS, so-called

00:10:38.960 --> 00:10:43.000
SCSS file into your Quarto document, set the theme to that file.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:48.320
It really is just a text file that you rename to something something dot SCSS, and then

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:50.559
you have an SCSS file.

00:10:50.559 --> 00:10:58.979
And in there, you can use, as I said, SCSS variables and set them to very specific values.

00:10:58.979 --> 00:11:05.380
This is really the easiest way you can style a lot of your Quarto outputs by figuring out

00:11:05.380 --> 00:11:07.900
what the couple of keywords are that you want to use.

00:11:07.900 --> 00:11:12.260
Here, the first three keywords are the primary and secondary and tertiary color.

00:11:12.260 --> 00:11:14.179
And I've just set them to some hex code.

00:11:14.179 --> 00:11:19.900
And by just setting this in this SCSS file, you can immediately transform the output of

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:20.900
your Quarto file.

00:11:20.900 --> 00:11:23.460
Basically, the theme is changed then.

00:11:23.460 --> 00:11:28.739
And the same thing could be done for the code background or the code chunk background

00:11:28.739 --> 00:11:30.940
colors and so on.

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:35.380
So you really have to figure out what is the keyword that I need, and then you set it to

00:11:35.380 --> 00:11:36.539
some value.

00:11:36.539 --> 00:11:40.979
And thankfully, the Quarto documentation is pretty solid on that part.

00:11:40.979 --> 00:11:47.059
You can just go to the Quarto website, look for the SAS variables, SCSS and SAS are kind

00:11:47.059 --> 00:11:48.460
of the same thing.

00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:55.099
And there, you will see the most important variables, and their names are kind of self-explanatory.

00:11:55.099 --> 00:11:57.659
And then set that to some value that you want.

00:11:57.659 --> 00:12:03.979
So that's basically the easy route to easier way into HTML and CSS with Quarto.

00:12:03.979 --> 00:12:10.460
And once you want to go wild, once you cannot do something with the basic SCSS variables

00:12:10.460 --> 00:12:16.260
to make the changes that you want, then it becomes time to look at the actual HTML and

00:12:16.260 --> 00:12:19.219
CSS code that Quarto generates for you.

00:12:19.219 --> 00:12:20.859
And on any website, you can do this.

00:12:20.859 --> 00:12:26.700
You can just take your web browser, right-click anywhere, a drop-down menu will appear, and

00:12:26.700 --> 00:12:28.679
then you can navigate to Inspect.

00:12:28.679 --> 00:12:32.020
Just imagine that there is Inspect and not the German word for it.

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:37.460
And then you would know what you have to click.

00:12:37.460 --> 00:12:42.799
I deliberately not clicked Inspect right now, because honestly, this part is scary.

00:12:42.799 --> 00:12:46.479
Once you open it up, the web developer view will immediately show up, and you will see

00:12:46.479 --> 00:12:47.919
a bunch of stuff.

00:12:47.919 --> 00:12:54.119
You will see the HTML, all the CSS, and 1,000 other tools I have never used, or I don't

00:12:54.119 --> 00:12:55.799
even know what they do, honestly.

00:12:55.799 --> 00:13:00.719
But really, it opens so many things, and you need someone to kind of guide you through

00:13:00.719 --> 00:13:01.719
it.

00:13:01.719 --> 00:13:07.080
But once you have that part, the strategy to make the changes that you want to learn

00:13:07.080 --> 00:13:11.080
HTML and CSS is pretty straightforward.

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:12.799
Select all the things that you want to change.

00:13:12.799 --> 00:13:19.359
This will immediately put you to the HTML and CSS code that generates that output.

00:13:19.359 --> 00:13:26.840
Copy and paste that stuff into your SCSS file, and then simply change the values to what

00:13:26.840 --> 00:13:27.840
you need.

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:31.239
So, as I said, you kind of need someone to guide you through it.

00:13:31.239 --> 00:13:37.119
You could, of course, try this at home and just click Inspect and see what's happening.

00:13:37.119 --> 00:13:40.640
But it's always easy to have someone show you where to look, how it works.

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:46.280
And once that is done, it's like a 10-minute intro, then you know how to operate with these

00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:47.280
three steps.

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:52.200
And then it really is as easy as I've said, copy and paste most of the things and add

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:54.799
the values after the fact.

00:13:54.799 --> 00:13:59.919
And that's why I decided to actually make such an introduction, because I cannot do

00:13:59.919 --> 00:14:00.919
this here.

00:14:00.919 --> 00:14:03.320
It would take too much time.

00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:10.520
So this is why you will find on YouTube a core-to-themes guide for HTML and CSS snoops

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:11.840
that guides you through that.

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:13.679
This is actually part two.

00:14:13.679 --> 00:14:19.000
Part one will show you more details on the first part that I have mentioned with the

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:20.679
SCSS variables.

00:14:20.679 --> 00:14:25.179
So you can start with part one, check out how far you can go with there, and then use

00:14:25.179 --> 00:14:30.080
part two to see how much you can get done with the web developer view.

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:32.919
And with that, thank you for coming for my talk.

00:14:32.919 --> 00:14:39.599
And I'm happy to answer any questions that you have.

00:14:39.599 --> 00:14:40.799
Thank you.

00:14:40.799 --> 00:14:43.760
We have indeed time for questions.

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:46.599
I was much faster than I practiced.

00:14:46.599 --> 00:14:52.919
So first question, have you dipped at all into JavaScript for enhancing your apps?

00:14:52.919 --> 00:14:56.080
Yeah, but this is like a scary world.

00:14:56.080 --> 00:15:01.400
I mean, I have dipped into it, and it is very fascinating what you can do.

00:15:01.400 --> 00:15:06.679
But I feel like the easier way to all the things you want to change for style, HTML

00:15:06.679 --> 00:15:10.760
and CSS are enough.

00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:16.159
What are the limitations of HTML and CSS in the R context?

00:15:16.159 --> 00:15:21.359
Like, I can't ask questions back, I guess.

00:15:21.359 --> 00:15:23.320
So I don't think there are any limitations.

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:27.679
I mean, basically all the websites in the world that you see are built on HTML and CSS,

00:15:27.679 --> 00:15:30.239
and you can see all varieties of websites.

00:15:30.239 --> 00:15:34.840
And I don't think there is, like, imagination is the limit for HTML and CSS.

00:15:34.840 --> 00:15:41.080
I guess the only thing that might be, like, in the R context be specific is, for example,

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:42.359
the ggtext example.

00:15:42.359 --> 00:15:44.799
It doesn't accept all style instructions.

00:15:44.799 --> 00:15:46.840
It only accepts those that were implemented.

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:49.799
In that kind of scenario, there truly is a limit.

00:15:49.799 --> 00:15:54.320
Then you would have to figure, like, something out.

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:59.599
So the ggtext output, that works not only in HTML output, right?

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:06.320
And that output can be, that's any ggplot, which you can save into a PDF file.

00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:12.960
I mean, at the end, it generates an image file, and the way that you need to instruct

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:15.640
to make the changes is via HTML and CSS code.

00:16:15.640 --> 00:16:20.440
I'm not 100% sure what ggtext does behind the scenes with that instruction, but you

